verdict.summary: The specified image tag or digest does not exist in the registry. The image may have been deleted, the tag misspelled, or the platform architecture not available.

dead_ends.action: Pulling with --platform flag when the image simply does not exist for that architecture
dead_ends.why_fails: If the image maintainer never published an arm64 variant, no platform flag will make it appear

dead_ends.action: Clearing local Docker cache hoping it will fix the pull
dead_ends.why_fails: The issue is server-side; the manifest genuinely does not exist in the registry

workarounds.action: Verify the exact image name, tag, and registry URL
workarounds.how: Check the registry web UI or use: docker manifest inspect <image>:<tag> to confirm the manifest exists

workarounds.action: Use a specific digest instead of a mutable tag
workarounds.how: docker pull image@sha256:<digest> â€” ensures you get the exact image that was verified to exist
workarounds.condition: when tags are being overwritten or deleted

leads_to.condition: when pulling a wrong-architecture image that happens to exist

preceded_by.condition: when authentication fails first, then manifest lookup fails

frequently_confused_with.distinction: manifest unknown typically means the tag never existed, while manifest not found can mean the tag was deleted or the repository path is wrong
